Oxfam is a global organization that fights inequality to end poverty and injustice. This grant to Oxfam America will support Oxfam’s implementation of the Women’s Economic Empowerment and Care (WE-Care) program in Ethiopia, Kenya, Uganda, and Zimbabwe, and support opportunities for influencing unpaid care and domestic work in regional and global spaces. The WE-Care program works to increase women’s and girls’ time and choice to participate in economic, political, and social life by transforming how unpaid care and domestic work is valued, shared, and invested in through supporting civil society and women’s rights organizations, educating men and boys and religious and cultural leaders, and conducting policy influencing. (Strategy: International Women’s Economic Empowerment)

BEOG NEERE is a nonprofit association under Burkinabè law. Founded in 2012 by young people and led by young people, BEOG NEERE works throughout Burkina Faso and Francophone Africa to promote the rule of law, democracy, and good governance. BEOG NEERE’s overall mission is to promote advocacy services to improve people's quality of life, social stability, and economic well-being. (Strategy: Inclusive Governance)

The Brookings Institution conducts in-depth research that leads to new ideas for solving problems facing society at the local, national, and global level. The Center for Sustainable Development at Brookings generates leading research and insights for advancing the development and implementation of the Sustainable Development Goals within and across countries. The center is committed to generating evidence, tools, and policy recommendations that support networked societal leadership for sustainable development. This grant will support the center in advancing a new program on gender and sustainable development. (Strategy: International Women’s Economic Empowerment).

Actions pour l’Environnement et le Développement Durable (ACED) is a think-and-do tank driving equitable development across Africa. ACED employs an integrated approach that combines research, policy engagement, and on-the-ground action. ACED focuses on four thematic areas: food systems, nature economy, digital economy, and human development. This grant project aims to improve social protection for informal women workers in Francophone West Africa, through macro-level policy solutions. Implementation for this grant hinges on two interconnected components: designing the implementation of locally relevant macro-level policy solutions, and increasing the technical capacity of policymakers and relevant stakeholders to design and implement these solutions. By working directly with ministries and various stakeholders in the social protection and informal economy sectors, this grant aims to improve the policy environment, thereby offering greater economic stability and equity for informal women workers in Francophone Africa. (Strategy: International Women's Economic Empowerment)

Advocates for Community Alternatives partners with communities in West Africa to explore community development alternatives that are not dependent on mining and carbon extraction. It will expand its community oversight initiative in the Donkro Nkwanta region of Ghana from the municipal to district level while deepening its West African regional partnerships for coordinated public interest litigation. (Strategy: Inclusive Governance)

ActionAid is an international network of organizations dedicated to social justice, poverty eradication, and gender equality in over 70 countries. Their work strengthens the agency of people living in poverty and partners with movements and grassroots leaders to develop holistic, community-led solutions to their most pressing challenges. ActionAid USA works at the U.S., regional, and international levels to advance ActionAid’s shared mission. In partnership with communities and organizations in the U.S. and around the world, ActionAid USA engages in advocacy and activism to undertake global policy efforts and mobilizes funds in support of ActionAid’s programs around the world. (Strategy: International Women’s Economic Empowerment)

Afrobarometer is a pan-African, nonpartisan survey research network that conducts public attitude surveys on democracy, governance, the economy, and society. The world’s leading source of high-quality data on what Africans are thinking, it has a network of more than 30 national partners responsible for data collection, analysis, and in-country dissemination of findings. Afrobarometer’s vision is a world in which Africa’s development is anchored in the realities and aspirations of its people. Afrobarometer will continue its efforts tomaking citizen voice a key pillar of African policy and decision making. (Strategy: Evidence-Informed Policymaking).

ActionAid USA is the U.S. branch of ActionAid International, which works in more than 50 countries to achieve social justice, gender equality, and poverty eradication. ActionAid builds international momentum for social, economic, and environmental justice, driven by people living in poverty and exclusion. This grant will support the convening of a group of strategic thinkers, including feminists, from across Africa on building a new economic paradigm to replace neoliberalism. (Strategy: International Women’s Economic Empowerment)

Afrobarometer is a pan-African, nonpartisan survey research network that conducts public attitude surveys on democracy, governance, the economy, and society. The world’s leading source of high-quality data on what Africans are thinking, it has a network of more than 30 national partners responsible for data collection, analysis, and in-country dissemination of findings. Afrobarometer’s vision is a world in which Africa’s development is anchored in the realities and aspirations of its people. Afrobarometer’s approach focuses on making citizen voice a key pillar of African policy and decision making. This grant will support Afrobarometer’s board development to manage governance leadership transition over the next year.
